<LEADPARA>  IN 1856 the towering and graceful eucalyptus tree was imported from Australia
to California, where its trunk was valued as a mast for sailing ships and its
branches for shade from summer's heat.;   The eucalyptus was a tree that soon
took over. Californians loved it because it was drought-tolerant, resistant to
insects and fast-growing. By the turn of the century the eucalyptus had become
the most widely planted non-native tree in the state and a symbol of good
living. Wealthy Californians grew eucalyptus by the acre and framed
wood-roofed mansions in the coastal hills above San Francisco Bay with groves
of the peppermint-scented tree.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Editorial  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  IN A DROUGHT, EUCALYPTUS TREES TURN MURDEROUS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related stories pages 1D and 4-7D, Editorial page 8D, and Commentary page
9D.; Commentary; Lou Cannon is a Washington Post columnist.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     But the eucalyptus tree became another kind of symbol last week. When a
wind-driven blaze roared through the Oakland hills, drought-dry eucalyptus
trees served as torches to pass the fire along from house to house. Within
minutes the firestorm had consumed houses, people, pets and wildlife in the
Hiller Highlands.;   For California, it was a calamitous warning of what Karen
Terrill of the state Department of Forestry called "the fire of the future."
Sixty percent of this most populous state is wildlands, and trees are much
prized here.;   Californians find it difficult, Terrill observed, "to get away
from the idea that a house is only attractive if it's dripping with trees
around it. It's very trendy in California to have that western, bushy look."; 
 Western trees and bushes catch fire, particularly in time of drought. On the
same day that Hiller Highlands and homes in the communities of Upper Rockridge
and Montclair were consumed by the fast-moving blaze, a dozen forest fires
raged on 80,000 acres in the West. But except in Oakland they burned in remote
areas where homes are few and far between.;   California, long a pioneer of
much that is best and worst in America, prides itself as being on the cutting
edge. Now, pressed by drought and relentless population growth, California is
exploring the outer limits of mixing urban growth and wildlands. And the
pattern is being followed in other Western states that I have visited recently
-- Nevada, Utah and Arizona -- where tracts of homes are rising amid trees in
areas where water is a luxury.;   Neither the urban nor the wildlands side of
the equation functioned last week in the Oakland hills. Budget cuts had forced
huge reductions in the Oakland firefighting force. The fire chief was new,
water pressure was inadequate and the department's radio equipment obsolete.
White firefighters, claiming to be victims of reverse discrimination, had sued
the city in objection to an affirmative action plan that mandated the
promotion of minorities and women.;   The lawsuit was settled 10 days before
the fire, with a federal judge ruling against the white firefighters and
upholding the city's plan. But while the case was making its way to
settlement, 50 vacancies on the fire department went unfilled. By almost any
measure, there were not enough firefighters in Oakland. And on the night of
Oct. 19, after the fire department contained a six-acre grass blaze, no
firefighters were left behind on the lines to see that the blaze did not flare
up again. On Sunday, the remnants of this small fire touched off the
conflagration.;   Once the fire began, even the most modern firefighting force
could not have stopped it. Too many homes were heaped in the wooden fuel of
bone-dry chaparral and the murderous eucalyptus trees. Many of the trees may
have been weakened by the eucalyptus longhorn beetle that is native to
Australia and did not make its way to Northern California until 1988. Some
trees had also been damaged or killed by last winter's severe freeze, for the
eucalyptus tree is thoroughly Californian in its intolerance of cold.;   In
the aftermath of the fire there was talk of uprooting the remaining eucalyptus
trees in the coastal hills where homes have thrust their way into wildlands.
And there was talk, too, of controlling development and requiring that brush
and trees be cleared from home sites in wooded areas throughout the state.
Such talk was heard last summer after the devastating Painted Cave Fire in
Santa Barbara, where residents are now building again amid the trees.;  
California, with its 30 million people, is a state constrained by urban and
outdoor realities. Mixing cities with wildlands in times of drought is
tempting nature. And as rancher and California Forestry Director Richard
Wilson observes, "In a contest with nature, nature usually wins."  </TEXT>
