<DESCRIPT>  GILROY; TREE; DISEASE; FOUND  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Dutch elm disease, a fungus that has killed millions of elm trees in North
America, has been found for the first time in Gilroy.;    The discovery has
officials in this proud "Tree City USA" worried because hundreds of Gilroy's
largest and most stately trees are European elms planted in the late 1800s by
pioneer rancher Henry Miller. The species is particularly susceptible to the
fatal fungus.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  KNOCK WOOD
DUTCH ELM DISEASE FOUND IN GILROY; 1,000
TREES IN JEOPARDY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Shorter version ran in the Morning Final edition.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The finding by state forestry officials means nearly 1,000 elms in and
around Gilroy are at risk and that residents should take special precautions
in handling the trees and their wood to prevent the spread of the fungus, said
Rick Brandini, Gilroy's urban forester.;    The infected tree was found on the
city's northeastern fringe, on the east side of Murray Avenue at Tomkins
Street, a good distance from other city elms.;    The 11-tree stand on Murray
Avenue and up to six other trees nearby, all in the 25-foot-tall range, have
been ordered destroyed by the state within 20 days and probably will be felled
Monday at an estimated cost of $1,500, Brandini said.;    The discovery means
Gilroy will be closely monitored by state forest department plant
pathologists.;    "We'll be looking closely at Gilroy every year until we're
sure it's cleared out," said Alleah B. Haley of the department's forestry pest
program.;    She said 1990 was the worst year on record for Dutch elm disease
in Santa Clara County, with 51 confirmed tree infestations, 47 of those in San
Jose.;    The Gilroy find, she said, was "not good news" because it moves the
known Bay Area range of the disease south by 21 miles.;    Except for a fluke
discovery in Beverly Hills in the 1970s, the disease in California up until
last year had been confined to the nine Bay Area counties, she said. Last
year, the disease was found in Sacramento and the delta town of Isleton.;   
Brandini said the only other species that can get the disease is the zelkova
tree, but Gilroy has only a few and most are on the high school campus, he
said.;    The Dutch elm fungus is spread by the tiny European elm bark beetle,
which carries its spores, feeds on twigs, and burrows and breeds under the
tree bark. It will breed under the bark whether the tree is alive or dying, or
whether the wood has been stacked or is in a pile of prunings.;    In fact,
dead and dying elm wood emits an odor that actually attracts the beetle,
Brandini said.;    The beetle, but not the disease, has probably been in
Gilroy as long as elms, he said.;    The initial discovery was made after
samples were taken in October during routine checks by state plant
pathologists.;    It was the first close examination of Gilroy's elms in four
years, Haley said.;    Far from major stands;    The only good news, Brandini
said, is that the infected tree is away from major stands in residential
areas, where the disease has not been detected.;    The state will take
special care when transporting the infected wood to the city landfill to be
chipped or buried, he said.;    Later, a systemic plant killer will be applied
to the stumps, which will then be removed along with roots.;    If the fungus
is found in residential areas, he said, insecticide sprays may be used to kill
the beetle. In the meantime, city crews and contract workers will go ahead
with already scheduled pruning operations on public trees, designed to strip
elms of dead and dying wood.;    Haley said California has been spared the
devastation the disease wreaked on the East Coast and in the Midwest because
elms are not native and California lacks sprawling stands of host trees.;   
In addition, a state program to keep the disease in check has operated with
good success since 1975.;    In all, state officials have inventoried 970
elms, mostly European and Siberian, in and near Gilroy. They're located on 527
parcels of property.;    The state will pick up the tab for the removal and
disposal of infected trees found on private property, Brandini said.;   
Symptoms displayed by diseased elms include portions of the tree or its leaves
wilting, then turning brown.;    The fungus clogs the tree's water-carrying
vessels, so its arboreal victims actually die from a lack of water, Brandini
said.;    He cautioned that the one-eighth-inch long, dark, fungus-carrying
beetle should not be confused with the lady bug-sized elm leaf beetle, a
different insect.;    Chewer, not carrier;  The latter does not carry the
disease and destroys leaves by chewing them, he said.;    Elm owners may
consider using sprays that kill the Dutch elm beetle in addition to carefully
pruning and burning dead or dying wood. Fall and winter are the best times to
prune elms, he said, adding that prevention is the way to deal with the
disease.;    Stately European elms, some in excess of 60-feet tall, line
Fifth, Sixth and Miller streets, among others, and represent the city's
tallest and some of its oldest trees, Brandini said.; IF YOU'RE
INTERESTEDResidents who need more information may call (408) 842-0221. If you
suspect you have a diseased elm, contact the forestry department's forestry
pest control program at (415) 837-4260.  </TEXT>
