<LEADPARA>  Kermit and Betty Smith are so upset they've fired off "help us" letters to a
string of city, county and state officials and the board of the Irvington
Square Homeowners Association.;   What's upset them are tiny ash whiteflies,
thousands of them -- maybe millions -- that invaded their property in
Irvington about a year ago. Since then, the leaves of the ash tree on their
front lawn have become a fly nursery.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  CLOUDS OF WHITEFLIES LOOK LIKE SNOW  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Inside Our Towns  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The Smiths call it "a growing epidemic that constitutes a public nuisance
and a safety hazard." They said the fly droppings create a "goo that seriously
impairs driving visibility. In addition to affecting automobile paint, this
sap is tracked into the house and all over rugs and linoleum.";   The ash
whiteflies, one of the most recent insects to invade California, can make
outdoor life miserable, testified Betty Smith, standing in front of her home
on Yorktown Road.;   "When you're outside, you have to keep your mouth shut or
they'll get in," she said.;   The whiteflies, which are attracted by the ash
trees along the street, can become so plentiful "that I can say without
exaggeration that you'd think it was snowing," she said.;   The whitefly,
first spotted in July 1988 near a fruit stand in the Los Angeles suburb of Van
Nuys, is mostly an urban problem, said Alameda County Agricultural
Commissioner Michael Greene. It defoliates trees, drips sticky, messy
droppings and swarms in dense clouds during the summer months. "It can be
nasty at a backyard barbecue," he said.;   The pest favors ash, pomegranate
and flowering pear trees. Its larvae suck plant juices from the underside of
leaves. It is pesticide-resistant and has few natural enemies.;   Whiteflies
somehow migrated here from either Europe or the Middle East. In three years,
the pest has spread over most of California, Nevada and Arizona.;   Greene
said that this summer, his office launched a war against the fly by releasing
1,000 stingless Encarsia wasps, an enemy of the whitefly. Two hundred and
fifty were released in Fremont, Livermore, Pleasanton and Hayward.;   The
little wasp, like the whitefly, is the size of the head of a ball-point pen.
The wasp lays its eggs in the scales of young whiteflies. As the wasp matures,
it feeds on the whitefly and kills it.;   The wasp was imported from Israel,
home of the ash tree. The wasps are natural parasites of the whitefly and
control their populations in Israel and other countries where the trees are
native.;   Greene said it is too early to tell who is winning the war. He
could not predict how long the war will go on.;   The wasp will never
eradicate the whitefly, but it should reduce whiteflies to a level where they
are no longer noticeable, Greene said. "They'll never be gone, but we can get
it down to a dull roar," he said.;   Meanwhile, small infestations of the
whitefly can be partially controlled with Lilly-Miller Fruit and Berry Insect
Spray. It is a mixture of malathion, methoxychlor and aromatic petroleum
solvents. This controls the adults and the larvae. The oil kills the eggs.
Spray weekly until control is achieved, says MercNews garden columnist Bob
Chapman.;   Betty Smith said she tried spraying.;   "But it didn't work. The
flies just came over from a neighbor's tree."  </TEXT>
