<LEADPARA>  A tiny parasitic wasp waging biological war on the tree-blighting ash whitefly
appears to be thriving in Southern California, one year after being introduced
at dozens of sites over a 12-county area.;    The wasp has been so successful
in the Riverside area that scientists have had to institute strict precautions
to ensure wild wasps do not wipe out the colony of ash whiteflies they
maintain in the laboratory for research purposes.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  IMPORTED WASP IS OFF TO FLYING START IN BIOLOGICAL
WAR ON WHITEFLY  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "It sounds a little strange, but we're at the point where we have to
protect our whiteflies from the parasites," said Tim Paine, a University of
California, Riverside entomologist.;    Buoyed by the success of the stingless
wasp imported from Israel, state agricultural officials began a second wave of
releases in Northern California last week that eventually will extend to an
additional 13 whitefly-infested counties, including Santa Clara, Alameda and
San Mateo counties.;    Informal surveys of secret Southern California release
sites last month found that most wasps not only survived last winter's freeze
but multiplied to the extent that some can be collected and spread elsewhere,
officials said.;    "The progress so far is very encouraging, and if it
continues at this pace we should see significant reductions in ash whitefly
populations in a few years," said Larry Bezark, manager of the state's ash
whitefly biocontrol program.;    Complaints from Los Angeles County residents
about the whitefly are down, a result county Agricultural Commissioner Leon
Spaugy attributes to the killing effects of the freeze as well as the wasps'
depredations.;    First spotted in July 1988 near a fruit stand in the Los
Angeles suburb of Van Nuys, the ash whitefly has been primarily an urban
problem, defoliating trees, dripping sticky, messy honeydew and swarming in
dense clouds during the summer months.;    Favoring ash, pomegranate and
flowering pear trees, the whitefly's larvae suck plant juices from the
underside of leaves. Pesticide-resistant and lacking natural enemies, the pest
-- a native of Europe and the Middle East -- has spread through most of
California and into Nevada and Arizona.;    Bred in laboratories in Sacramento
and Riverside, the black-and-gold Encarsia wasps are released to lay their
eggs on whitefly larvae. After the eggs hatch, the wasps eat the larvae from
the inside, emerging when they mature.;    Although the wasp will never
eradicate the whitefly, the tiny parasite -- along with other natural enemies
that may be released later -- should reduce whiteflies to a level where they
are no longer noticeable, officials said.;    The arctic front that clamped
California in its icy grip last December killed thousands of ash whiteflies,
leaving scientists worried that the wasps would suffer a similar fate.;    But
last month's surveys by state and county entomologists found most wasp
colonies had survived -- even in one Santa Barbara County location where the
temperature had dropped to 25 degrees, Bezark said.;    "In a large majority
of the release sites -- seven out of eight in Los Angeles County, for example
-- the number of parasites are up and whiteflies are down," he said. "They are
even turning up in places you wouldn't expect them to be in.";    Researchers
found the wasps had traveled unaided up to 18 miles from one of their original
release points in Riverside County and about half that distance in neighboring
San Bernardino County, he said.;    The wasps' success there and in San Diego
County will allow scientists to carry out the program's second phase: using
the new colonies as nurseries where wasps can be collected for distribution
elsewhere.;    In Tulare County, where December temperatures dropped as low as
15 degrees, surveys of release sites have not yet found any wasps, said Dennis
Haines, staff biologist for the county agricultural commissioners' office.;   
Because the San Joaquin Valley has greater extremes of heat and cold than most
of Southern California, scientists will be carefully monitoring the progress
of wasps released this summer.  </TEXT>
