<HEAD>Forget Killer Bees; the Ash Whitefly Is Here</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   James Walters worked for the AP as a reporter
and editor from 1947 until he retired in 1984.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JAMES E. WALTERS</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   To most gardeners in this country, whiteflies are
minor nuisances that look like flakes of dandruff when disturbed.
But forget foreign invaders like killer bees, fire ants and
Japanese beetles. The ash whitefly now is in the United States.
   So far it's been spotted mainly around Los Angeles, but Dave
Langston, entomologist for the University of Arizona-State
Extension Service, says there are some suspicious areas in Arizona
and he's pretty sure confirmed outbreaks will be found this summer
in this state and possibly others.
   That would be consistent with California's experience.
``California Agriculture,'' published by the University of
California, says in the January-February edition that since the
first North American report of ash whitefly in the summer of 1988,
``populations have reached extraordinary levels in Los Angeles
County and may affect fruit and nursery crops throughout the
state.''
   The scientific name of this super whitefly is Siphoninus
phillyreae. First recorded in 1835, it's now known in most of
Europe, northern Africa, the Middle East, southern Russia, Pakistan
and India. Natural enemies limit severe outbreaks in the Old World.
Unfortunately, there don't seem to be any on this continent.
California is experimenting this spring with imported biological
controls, including a tiny wasp.
   Meantime, gardeners should be prepared.
   Insecticides never have been effective against even our native
whiteflies. But for the most part, damage has been isolated.
   The ash whitefly is like comparing a tiger to a cat. Climate,
hot or cold, doesn't seem a problem. It reproduces in about 25 days
and passes through four stages, all of which feed by sucking sap
from leaves. There frequently are reports of clusters on every leaf
of a mature tree. Adults often are inhaled or caught in people's
eyes. Known hosts, besides ash trees, include citrus, olive,
pomegranate, jujube, apple, peach, pear, loquat, apricot, plum and
many ornamental shrubs and trees.
   The common name, ash whitefly, was applied in this country after
the first ones were found on ash trees. In Europe it's usually
known as the pear whitefly or peach whitefly, because of damage to
those crops. Some textbooks call it the pomegranate whitefly.
   Whiteflies were more numerous than usual last year in Arizona.
Is it possible some were ash whitefly?
   ``Not a chance,'' says Langston. ``Once you get this one you'll
know it. Trees turn yellow. Some die. It's not like now, when you
get just honeydew and whiteflies flying around. These aren't
necessarily any bigger in size, but they feed a lot more and suck
large quantities of fluid. So there's major symptoms on foliage.''
   ``California Agriculture'' says, ``Populations grow to enormous
densities ... often covering 100 percent of available foliage and
producing substantial amounts of honeydew and sooty molds.''
   To entomologists, appearance of the species is unique because of
40 to 50 tiny, dorsal, siphon tubes in the pupal stage. But
whiteflies are too small for gardeners to spot this. So damage will
be the clue.
   ``I think this summer we'll see a couple isolated cases in
Arizona where we'll have to treat for it,'' says Langston. ``What
we'll use I have no idea, since I understand nothing works.
Biological control probably is the ultimate answer.''
   Pesticide treatment, in the California experience, may be
successful in small areas, such as nurseries. Sprays or water or
insecticidal soap seem to reduce the population on smaller plants.
However, re-infestation is likely from nearby vegetation.
   Many nursery-trade groups and government agencies, including the
California Department of Food and Agriculture, are participating
with the University of California in the biological control
program. Encarsia wasps supplied by Israel and Italy have been
promising in field tests. The wasps reproduce by laying eggs inside
ash whitefly nymphs, which are eaten by the wasp larvae.
   The ash whitefly probably entered this country on plants sent to
Los Angeles either by air or sea, according to ``California
Agriculture.'' Infestation in Los Angeles County was widespread
when first reported. Just-detectable levels were found then in an
adjoining county. However, between the following spring and autumn,
that infestation grew to nearly equal that in Los Angeles.
</TEXT>
