<LEADPARA>  THE EXPERTS say don't use pesticides to control those swarms of whiteflies in
your yard because pesticides will kill the good-guy predator insects, too.;  
But what about organic, or natural, controls? And what about the all-important
dormant sprays applied to deciduous fruit trees in winter?  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  DON'T USE PESTICIDES, EXPERTS WARN
READERS SEEK REMEDIES FOR WHITEFLIES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 1D of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Here are some of the questions our readers are asking, with the answers
from entomologists and other sources:;   Q Can I spray my fruit trees with
horticulture oil, or will this hurt the wasps and parasites?;   A Gardeners
planning to use dormant sprays or chemicals to prevent peach leaf curl needn't
worry about harming the ash-whitefly parasites, says Dr. Tim Paine, assistant
professor with the University of California, Riverside, entomology
department.;   The whiteflies -- and the parasites -- live on tree leaves.
Since dormant oil sprays are applied after the tree drops its foliage, the
insects won't be present.;   The whiteflies and parasites will spend the
winter on trees that don't drop their leaves such as citrus, evergreen pear,
pyracantha and toyon. Those trees shouldn't be sprayed, Paine says.;   Q I've
had good luck with a homemade spray of Ivory soap and water. Now I'm wondering
if this is a good idea?;   A You can use non-detergent household soaps such as
Ivory Snow, Ivory Liquid or Shaklee's Basic H with varying degrees of
success.;   Start with from one teaspoon to one tablespoon of soap per gallon
of water. Rodale's "Chemical-Free Yard and Garden" ($23.95) warns that all
soaps, whether homemade or commercial, will damage plants if used repeatedly
or mixed at high concentrations. Three successive sprays on any particular
plant should be the limit.;   Keep in mind, also, that all soapy sprays are a
type of insecticide, and Paine, for one, isn't thrilled with the method.;  
"Spraying soap works. It's a poison, a chemical. But there are problems with
spraying anything. Like spraying pesticides, they only work for about a week
and then the trees are reinfested. If you spray a lot of plants with soap, you
break down the cuticle and the plant is susceptible to burning," he says.;  
"We don't know if it kills the parasites, but we have no reason to believe
that it doesn't. It's better to let the parasites build up. Let them go to
work," he says.;   Q What's the story on sticky whitefly traps? Are they worth
the effort?;   A We've gotten mixed reviews on this. Whiteflies are attracted
to a specific shade of yellow so they can be trapped on boards painted that
color and coated with a sticky material. The down side is the predator insects
may be trapped, also.;   In "Common-Sense Pest Control" (Taunton Press,
$39.95), the suggestion is to cut cardboard or plywood into 1-by-2-foot pieces
and paint them on both sides with Rustoleum Yellow No. 659. After the paint
dries, coat both sides with a sticky substance such as Tanglefoot, Tack Trap,
or Stickem Special. Then hang the boards as close as possible to the plants
infested with whiteflies.;   John Louzensky of Saratoga says he has had good
luck using yellow Penzoil containers coated with motor oil. He picked up 30
empty containers at a gas station, coated each one with STP motor oil and set
them on the ground around his yard. "I used to have swarms of whiteflies. I
notice my neighbors are doing the same thing now," he says. Once a week he
wipes off the containers and repeats the process.;   An adhesive that is easy
to remove, according to "Common-Sense Pest Control," is two parts petroleum
jelly such as Vaseline, or mineral oil, to one part household detergent or
insecticidal soap. Apply a thin coat on yellow boards or yellow containers.;  
There are also commercial sticky whitefly traps available.;   Whether the
traps really make a difference is another matter. Paine, for one, says, "If
it's satisfying to people to do it, and they want to watch whiteflies die, go
ahead.";   "But," he says, "you're talking about (killing) several thousand
whiteflies with the traps and there are millions or billions in the
population. We can't tell anyone they can't use them, but they aren't going to
make a major impact.";   Q I read about using a vacuum to suck up whiteflies.
Does this work?;   A Like the sticky whitefly traps, vacuuming may work but it
won't make a major impact on the whitefly swarms. There is also the risk of
sucking up parasites and wasps.;   "Common-Sense Pest Control" says vacuuming
should be done in the early morning when whiteflies are cold and slow-moving.
Use a small, hand-held battery-operated vacuum such as Dustbuster Plus.;  
After vacuuming up the adults, enclose the bag in plastic and put it in the
freezer for 24 hours to kill the insects. Don't put the whole vacuum in the
freezer because it will be damaged.;   On the flip side, if the adult
whiteflies have been around awhile laying eggs, vacuuming alone will not halt
the infestation, write "Common-Sense Pest Control" authors William Olkowski,
Sheila  Dear and Helga Olkowski. They are founders of the Bio-Integral
Resource Center (BIRC) in Berkeley.;   Q Whitefly are particularly bad on my
lemon tree. Has the combined effects of the drought and last year's freeze
weakened this tree and made it more likely to be damaged by whiteflies?;   A
The experts say there is no particular link between the two. But common sense
indicates that trees that have had a hard time, especially the citrus trees,
would be unable to combat a whitefly invasion.;   Water these weakened trees,
and once a week blast off the whiteflies with a spray of water.;   Q I've read
about the whitefly's predators. Are they really effective? How long will it
take for them to do their job?;   A The predators, a tiny wasp and a beetle,
were imported from Europe and Africa, home of the ash whiteflies. When the
predator insects were released in Southern California in 1989, the population
"fell 10,000-fold," said Tim Paine, assistant professor of entomology at
University of California, Riverside. "We used to average 100 whitefly nymphs
per leaf. We now average one nymph per 100 leaves.";   If those same predator
insects do their job in the South Bay, Paine said, "Two years from now you'll
be saying, 'Something is different here. We can't find whiteflies.' "  </TEXT>
