<LEADPARA>  Last month's great freeze will lead to increased fire hazards in some Bay Area
regions this summer because of severe damage to eucalyptus groves.;   
Thousands of the popular trees, imports from Australia that don't weather cold
temperatures well, have turned brown on hillsides in the East Bay and Santa
Cruz Mountains.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Local  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FREEZE'S LEGACY IS FIRE
DAMAGED TREES INCREASE HAZARD  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "They look pretty funny, huh?" said John Nicoles, a land management
specialist for the East Bay Regional Park District, referring to the drooping
and discolored trees that run along the East Bay ridge line through Berkeley
and Oakland.;    Forestry and park officials said that although they don't
expect the trees to die, huge bunches of dead leaves may hang onto treetops
well into the fire season, creating a "fuel ladder" that significantly
increases firefighting hazards.;    "Your flames now will not only be on the
ground, but they can climb up the ladder into the tree crown, making a very
intense fire," said Rodger Thompson, a forester with the California Department
of Forestry and Fire Protection in Santa Cruz County.;    Thompson surveyed
tree damage in the Corralitos and Watsonville areas on Friday, where he said
the eucalyptus trees "took the freeze very hard.";    Nicoles said the freeze
did not appear to be as severe as the last similar episode, in December 1972,
when temperatures in the East Bay's upper elevations didn't rise above
freezing for five straight days. Temperatures last month dipped to as low as
11 degrees overnight at 1,500 feet in Berkeley, but daytime readings usually
broke the freezing mark.;    He said long-term damage to the forest is "a real
iffy question." After the 1972 freeze, the district thought many trees had
died that actually survived. While the leaf kill looks bad, new leaves should
sprout this year.;    "I do not see this as being a crisis," Nicoles said.
"I'm not worried yet, but I may be by the end of March" if the trees don't
show signs of life.;    Thompson said an examination of the tree stems also
indicated that most of the trees will survive in his region.  </TEXT>
