<LEADPARA>  MORE than one person is cursing "those damn eucalyptus" as the fuel that
ignited the Oakland hills tragedy. Officials in Berkeley are talking about
banning their planting.;   But thousands of eucalyptus trees grow in hilly
areas throughout the California coastal area. Planted in woodlots in the
1920s, the eucalyptus have gone wild, taking over hillsides and driving out
native plants, much to the dismay of naturalists, who have long opposed their
planting in California.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ON THE LINE
OIL-LADEN EUCALYPTUS ADD HOT FUEL TO FIRES ON DRY
CALIFORNIA HILLS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related stories on P. 1D and 2D of this section  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Alive or dead, drought or not, the trees are serious fire hazards.;   "Most
eucalyptus have highly flammable oil in the branches. They are designed to
burn hot and fast in such a way that the fruit opens and the seeds are
released without burning. That is the way they've evolved and that is why they
keep coming back," says Brett Hall, manager at the University of California,
Santa Cruz, arboretum, where dozens of eucalyptus species are cultivated.;  
Because of the way they grow, getting rid of eucalyptus would be a major job.
Reseeding is just part of the problem. When eucalyptus is cut down, it puts up
new shoots from the stump or roots, which in turn develop into new, full-size
trees in less than 10 years.;   Hall says a drought-stressed eucalyptus "burns
almost as fast and hot as a dead eucalyptus. It's that flammable. The branches
are pure fuel.";   The irony is that eucalyptus is valued as excellent
firewood because it burns at a high temperature and produces a lot of heat.;  
The Blue Gum is the story of a California dream gone awry. The trees where
brought here from Australia in the 1920s as a source for timber. A bad idea,
it turned out, because the wood was too brittle for lumber use.;   But by
then, those first stands of fast-growing trees were spreading seed throughout
the coastal area of California. Now the Blue Gum of the species Eucalyptus
globulus is the most widely grown eucalyptus in the state. There are some 800
species of eucalyptus, and Sunset Western Garden Book lists 57 types for use
in California landscapes.;   Hall is unhappy that the Blue Gum "has given all
eucalyptus a bad name because of the fire.";   Shrub eucalyptus are attractive
to butterflies, bees and birds. In fact, most of the Central Coast's monarch
butterfly population is in partial eucalyptus groves. Small tree varieties,
and shrub types, are used as wind breaks and screens, and some are valued for
their attractive bark and flowers.;   But even Sunset cautions that the Blue
Gum is too messy, greedy and brittle for yard or city use, noting, "They need
deep roots and plenty of room and are best on coastal slopes.";   Which is
just where they were when the wind, blowing from the East, began fanning
Sunday's fire. It was then that their sap began to boil, forcing whole trees
to explode in one big whoosh.  </TEXT>
