<CAPTION>  Drawing; DRAWING: Illustration by Wilfred Spoon; (Eucalyptus tree)  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  AUSTRALIA; TREE; HISTORY; CALIFORNIA  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  YOU MIGHT THINK OF THOSE GRACEFUL, swaying trees soaring above the roadway as
congenitally Californian. You'd be wrong, yet they're so identified with the
state that they have nearly the clout of natives. Just try to cut down one,
let alone a grove -- you'll find defenders who couldn't be bothered with a
scrub oak or a stand of madrone.;    Eucalyptus is native to Australia.
Several hundred species grow down under in a variety of soils and habitats --
just about everywhere between the heart of the rain forests and the deserts
and steppes. Their adaptability and seeming utility prompted transplantation
throughout the world, particularly in the last half of the 19th century.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  West  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  EUCALYPTUS
EUCALYPTUSES HAVE THEIR ENEMIES, BUT THEY
DO TRY TO FIT IN.  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  WEST PRIMER
JIM BETTINGER is deputy director of the John S. Knight Fellowships at Stanford.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The first eucalypts in California were planted in a San Francisco garden
around 1853. Over the next decade a handful were planted here, a handful
there. Meanwhile a California educator became convinced that the deforestation
of the United States was imminent. With a fitting 19th century optimism,
Elwood Cooper believed there was a man-made solution to this problem.;    On a
ranch north of Santa Barbara he planted 50,000 eucalypts and began to spread
the word.;    What ensued was described as "The Eucalyptus Crusade" by Viola
Lockhart Warren in Southern California Quarterly: "With the naive mixture of
patriotism and acquisitiveness that Ellwood Cooper had inspired, Southern
California began to plant. . . . Cooper had recommended windbreaks planted at
right angles with the prevailing direction of the wind, and windbreaks were
planted. Cooper wanted the highways lined with trees, closely planted and two
or three rows deep, and the inspired landholders edged their property with
belts of little seedlings and watered them carefully for the first year.";   
The crusade hit warp speed after the Forest Service predicted that U.S.
eastern hardwoods would be cut and gone by 1920. Visions of gold eagles danced
in growers' heads, fueled by testimonials from furniture makers, flooring
firms, dry-dock builders -- and that didn't count the byproducts that could be
distilled from the oil and resin.;    The first trees harvested had problems
-- the wood had to be sawn into lumber right away, before it became unworkable
-- but these were thought to be speed bumps. They turned out to be brick
walls. It didn't matter how the wood was cut, or when, or what was done to it
after: It warped, it cracked, it twisted.;    Other drawbacks began to
surface. The roots were as invasive as Saddam Hussein, breaking cisterns and
water pipes as they burrowed for water. As a street tree, eucalypts were a
bust. After any good windstorm you'll still see lanes blocked by leaves, bark,
branches and, in a good season, whole trees. They crack and fall no matter how
well you're tending to them in good times, let alone the conditions that have
freeze-dried so many of them recently.;    Good riddance, you might say.
(Especially if a previous lord of your manor planted one in your back yard.)
And yet, and yet. . . . Woodman, spare that tree! We need the scent, if
nothing else. No one who has walked through a stand of eucalyptus, perhaps
early in the fall when the scimitar leaves have absorbed a summer's worth of
heat, can forget that aroma, or wish never to smell it again.;    They came to
California to take it over, but were humbled by their limitations, the way a
lot of us are. They're good citizens -- new to the neighborhood but learning
its ways. Indeed, a windbreak of these immigrants might tame the odoriferous
wind that threatens a South Bay baseball stadium. "If you mix eucalyptus and
chlorine," says the official stadium odor consultant, "you smell eucalyptus."
And so the team that took the field would have to be not the San Francisco
Giants, not the San Jose Giants, but the Eucalyptus Giants.  </TEXT>
