<LEADPARA>  MANY drought-stressed trees in California forests and yards are under attack
by bark beetles, according to several researchers at the University of
California College of Natural Resources at Berkeley.;    Entomologist David
Wood says bark beetles are causing "unprecedented mortality" in the state's
coniferous forests.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BARK BEETLES ARE DESTROYING FIRS AND PINES
IN PARKS, YARDS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Spring Garden Special  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     Large groups of pines and firs are being killed by the western pine beetle,
mountain pine beetle and fir engraver beetle. The mortality is thought to
result from the drought, which has weakened the trees so that the beetles can
successfully overcome the defense systems of the trees.;    Several other
researchers are developing a computer data bank to help county directors in UC
Cooperative Extension offices around the state to obtain tree diagnoses,
evaluate potential damage and receive treatment options.;  IF YOU'RE
INTERESTED;    For more information, contact Richard Harris at the Department
of Forestry and Resource Management at (415) 642-2360.  </TEXT>
