<HEAD>Dry Weather Has Forest Officials Worried About Devastating Fire
Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drought-Diner, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE TIBBITS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A year after one of the worst summer fire seasons
this century for the nation's forests, government and timber
industry officials are worried the drought may be bringing even
more devastating conditions.
   In some parts, ``the conditions we are experiencing now are very
similar to what we would expect to be experiencing in August, at
the height of the fire season,'' said Paul Weeden, a U.S. Forest
Service emergency operations specialist in Washington, D.C.
   Although there are ``pockets of wetness'' in some forests,
Weeden said Wednesday, most of the nation has a high fire danger,
with some areas facing very high or extreme risks. Many areas are
in their second year or more of drought, he said, with the
hardest-hit areas in the Pacific Northwest, California and parts of
the Southeast, particularly North Carolina.
   The dry weather also wilts tree seedlings, slows growth and
makes trees more susceptible to insects, especially bark beetles,
Weeden said.
   If dry conditions continue for another month, an estimated 5.7
billion board feet of timber could be lost to the quarter-inch
beetles, which eat the cambium between the tree's bark and wood, he
said.
   ``That's a pretty significant number because the average annual
allowable cut for the Forest Service is about 11 billion board
feet,'' he said.
   Weyerhaeuser Co. expects to lose 15 percent of its 38 million
seedlings in the South because of the drought, said John McMahon,
vice president of timberlands. Last year, McMahon told The Wall
Street Journal in an article published Wednesday, Weyerhaeuser had
to replant 4 percent of its seedlings nationwide.
   Fire is the most immediate threat to the nation's dry forests.
   Last year, fires burned almost 5 million acres of government and
private timber, worth $1.2 billion, Weeden said. It was the worst
fire year for federal lands since 1919.
   One of the largest fires so far this year burned 58,300 acres of
parched timber and grasslands in and near the Custer National
Forest along the Montana-South Dakota border. Firefighters brought
it under control Wednesday.
   In Wyoming, erratic winds hindered 389 firefighters trying to
control a 1,150-acre fire that was sparked by lightning and
threatened critical grizzly bear and bald eagle habitat in the
Shoshone National Forest.
   And Southern California firefighters battled two Riverside
County brush fires that charred 1,125 acres. Authorities hoped to
encircle the largest blaze, 1,000 acres, by tonight.
   Nearly 800,000 acres of California timberland were lost to fire
last year, and officials are edgy. Even though the state's forests
got some rain recently, ``We're still in extreme danger,'' said
Roberta Andersen, vice president of the Timber Association of
California in Sacramento.
   ``The fire season started real early,'' said Brian Barrette,
staff chief for the California Department of Forestry and Fire
Protection. ``It was running at least six weeks ahead of normal.''
   Temperatures cooled in May, but not enough to affect the
dried-out trees in many California forests, Barrette said. With a
30- to 60-day outlook for above-normal temperatures, ``it's a
pretty good indication that we'll have some real problems,'' he
said.
   In the Northwest, the Cascade Mountains divide the fire danger:
On the wetter west side, conditions are about normal, but to the
east, forests are facing a fourth consecutive dry year.
   ``There was no significant rain this spring. The little bit of
rain we did get gave us good growths of grasses and brush that are
beginning to dry out,'' said Marty Ames, spokeswoman for the
Wenatchee National Forest in central Washington. ``It doesn't look
like the weather is going to bring any relief.''
