<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Can these old oaks be saved?  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  TREE; PARK; SACRAMENTO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A GROUP dedicated to saving the disappearing oaks that once spread their huge
canopies throughout the Central Valley celebrated the first California Native
Oak Day by planting a spindly, eight-foot valley oak in Capitol Park.;  
"Tremendous numbers of these trees existed at one time in California," said
Sen. Dan McCorquodale, D-San Jose, author of the resolution passed by the
Legislature naming Nov. 1 as California Native Oak Day.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Garden  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  FOUNDATION PLANTS TREE IN CAPITOL PARK
A HOPEFUL MOVE TO PRESERVE OAKS  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Update  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "It is easy to cut a tree. It is very difficult to grow a tree,
particularly an oak tree," said Jane Hagedorn, founder of the California Oak
Foundation.;   Hagedorn, McCorquodale and other foundation members grinned as
they used a gold-plated ceremonial shovel to toss dirt into the hole
surrounding the young tree.;   Hagedorn, former president of the Sacramento
Tree Foundation, and other civil leaders, conservationists and arborists
formed the California Oak Foundation in 1988. She said it was started "knowing
we were losing this precious heritage and there was no one out there to be an
advocate for it.";   California has 15 species of oak, including several
native only to the state. The trees once dominated the Central Valley, their
acorns providing food for California Indians. But many species, particularly
valley oak, blue oak and Engelmann oak, have been greatly diminished by
large-scale clearing for development, farming and flood control.;  
McCorquodale said when the Senate Natural Resources Committee, which he
chairs, held a hearing on the oak several years ago, "it seemed there were
more symbols of oak trees than there were oak trees." He said firms were using
the oak as a symbol and cities used the tree in names, but no one was doing
anything to preserve the trees.;   The foundation now has more than 2,000
members and "I am cautiously optimistic that we will save this resource for
our children," Hagedorn said.;   The foundation's goal is to improve public
knowledge of oaks and promote both saving existing trees and planting new
ones.;   The foundation is publishing a new book, "Oaks of California" by
Bruce Pavlik, Pam Muick and Sharon Johnson, next month. It also has a pamphlet
called "Compatible Plants Under and Around Oaks," and a brochure suggesting
oak-related classroom projects called "Seed to Seedling."  </TEXT>
