<DESCRIPT>  CALIFORNIA; STATE; TREE; REGULATION  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The state Department of Forestry intends to come up with a new plan to
restrict the harvest of immature trees in coastal Northern California, despite
the state Board of Forestry's refusal Tuesday to declare an emergency and
limit the harvest.;    The board, an industry-dominated panel made up entirely
of appointees of former Gov. George Deukmejian, concluded that the rapid
harvest of redwoods and other trees in recent years does not threaten the
long-term supply of timber in California.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  STATE LOOKS AT NEW LOGGING RESTRICTIONS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The California Department of Forestry and Fire Protection, alarmed by an
increasing number of industry proposals to log immature stands of trees, had
asked the board to approve emergency regulations restricting the size of trees
that loggers could cut. But the board voted 6-0 to reject the proposal.;    On
Wednesday, Ken Delfino, the Forestry Department's deputy director for
resources, said he will return to the board with regulations that are similar
but would be implemented on the regular state timetable for adopting rules
rather than the streamlined schedule that requires declaration of an
emergency.;    With the defeat of two rival timber initiatives on the ballot
last year, the issue of over-cutting has emerged as one of the major questions
facing Gov. Pete Wilson and the Legislature. The governor, who oversees the
Forestry Department, has called for a policy of sustained yield, in which the
timber harvest does not exceed the forests' annual growth rate.;    At the
same time, a group of Northern California lawmakers has pledged to push
through the Legislature a compromise drafted by environmentalists and one
timber company that would place a variety of new restrictions on the logging
industry.;    But Wilson missed an opportunity to promote the emergency
regulations: Since January, the Board of Forestry has had three vacancies,
including the post of chairman, and the governor has yet to fill any of the
seats. Spokesmen for Wilson said he has been too preoccupied with the state's
budget deficit and drought to focus on the appointments.;    For years, the
timber industry has been under pressure from environmentalists to halt logging
of old-growth trees. More recently, industry critics have protested that
loggers are taking trees that are less than 50 years old and have not yet
reached their period of most rapid growth.;    The emergency regulations
proposed by the department would have affected about 1.4 million acres of
immature forest, more than half of the timberland on the North Coast,
department officials said.;    Dozens of landowners and industry
representatives vigorously opposed the proposed logging restrictions.;   
"What business does the state have in dictating when a landowner should
harvest his crop?" argued Jim Holmes, a forester with Simpson Lumber Co.  </TEXT>
