<LEADPARA>  One of California's largest timber companies, Louisiana-Pacific Corp., said
Wednesday it would phase out clear-cutting on company-owned land in the
state.;    In a statement from the company's Portland headquarters, Chairman
Harry Merlo said clear-cutting -- the controversial practice of removing all
the trees in an area -- wasn't bad for forests, but was bad for public
relations.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  California News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  TIMBER GIANT VOWS TO END CLEAR-CUTTING ON
ITS LAND  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News wire services contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "It comes under frequent criticism for the way it looks for the first
several years following a harvest," Merlo said.;    The promise to stop
clear-cutting by 1994 comes four months after California voters narrowly
defeated a sweeping forestry-reform initiative that would have banned
clear-cutting. Referring specifically to the defeated Proposition 130, Merlo
said the company was responding to "genuine interest and concern in California
about how trees are grown, harvested and converted into products.";    But
skeptical environmentalists noted that Louisiana-Pacific traditionally uses
little clear-cutting. They suggested the announcement was timed to head off
forestry-reform efforts in the Legislature and potentially restrictive rules
from the state Board of Forestry.;    "We're not impressed," said Gary Ball,
president of the Mendocino Environment Center, where Louisiana-Pacific owns
most of its 500,000 acres in California. He said the company would continue to
use "shelterwood" cuts, which he described as "a clear-cut done in stages.";  
 Environmentalists complain that clear-cutting is visually unattractive,
contributes to erosion and distorts natural processes, because all the trees
in an area are rarely felled by fires or storms.;    Representatives of other
environmental groups were more favorable. "This is a large, bold step in the
proper direction," said Gail Lucas, head of the Sierra Club's forest-practices
task force.;    However, Lucas said the announcement did little to resolve
concerns about the rate at which trees are being cut along the North Coast, or
Louisiana-Pacific's plan to convert most of its redwood and Douglas firs to
young trees that would be broken down and recombined into "wood products.";   
Lucas is one of three environmentalists who have been meeting with
representatives of Sierra Pacific Co. in hopes of developing a forestry-reform
package -- addressing the same issues but less severely than Proposition 130
-- for the Legislature. The proposal could face opposition from more radical
environmentalists and other timber companies, however.;    Wednesday, other
major timber companies -- including Georgia-Pacific Corp. and Simpson Redwood
Co. -- said they did not plan to eliminate clear-cutting.;   
Louisiana-Pacific, which does not use clear-cutting outside California, said
it would continue to clear-cut in national forests, where the harvesting
method is determined by the U.S. Forest Service.;    Combined with reduced
timber sales in national forests and cutting restrictions to protect the
endangered Northern spotted owl, Merlo said the elimination of clear-cutting
would reduce Louisiana-Pacific's California harvests by 40 percent.  </TEXT>
