<BYLINE>By SANDRA WALEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida's agriculture commissioner announced
Tuesday the state will begin aerial pesticide spraying to combat an
infestation of Mediterranean fruit flies.
   A malathion compound will be sprayed by helicopter beginning
Thursday in a mostly residential, 16-square-mile area, commissioner
Doyle Conner said at a news conference.
   The spraying will continue for four weeks followed by the
release of millions of sterile Medflies over a 75-day period to
break the breeding cycle. Fruit quarantine boundaries have not yet
been established.
   Six of the crop-destroying pests have been discovered near Miami
International Airport, including two on Tuesday.
   Conner said the eradication program has proven successful and is
the best approach, despite environmental concerns raised over
similar sprayings in California.
   Consumer activists and local governments in Southern California
have protested the repeated spraying of malathion-laced syrup on
suburban neighborhoods. The Medfly has spread from suburban back
yards to orange and grapefruit groves in some of the region's
richest farmland.
   ``Those who advocate deviating from accepted scientific
procedures, you run into the grave risk of getting into the
predicament California is in,'' Conner said. ``We don't want to
stay in this program a day longer than necessary.''
   Bobby McKown, executive vice president of Florida Citrus Mutual
in Lakeland, said Monday the 12,000-member growers' organization
supports ``immediate action to control and eradicate the Medflies
so they don't expand beyond residential areas.''
   Medflies, considered one of the world's most serious
agricultural pests, are about half the size of houseflies. They do
not sting and pose no threat to humans, but the larvae hatching
inside more than 250 varieties of fruits and vegetables can turn it
to inedible mush.
   Conner said the 2.4 ounces of malathion to be sprayed per acre
with a syrupy insect food bait posed no health risk, but an
environmentalist blasted the announcement.
   ``The bad thing about using these kinds of chemicals is that
they wipe out all the insects in an area _ the good and the bad,''
said Lee Emerson, vice president of the environment group Friends
of the Oleta River.
   It's not the kind of balanced, environmentally sensitive
approach we should be taking these days,'' he said.
   The zone to be sprayed covers suburban Miami Springs, Virginia
Gardens, part of Hialeah and unincorporated areas northwest of
downtown Miami. The latest fly was found Tuesday in Virginia
Gardens.
   The Florida Medfly Advisory Group, which includes Medfly experts
from the U.S. Department of Agriculture, expanded the area of
intensive trapping Monday from 81 to 106 square miles and beefed up
the inspection staff.
   Traps were set in fruit trees by state agricultural inspectors
around Dade County following the discovery April 16 of a lone male
Medfly near the airport. Two more males were found last weekend in
sour-orange trees in Miami Springs and Hialeah, and one female in a
calamondin tree in Miami Springs.
   Some 60,000 gallons of malathion in a stronger concentration,
about 3.1 ounces per acre, are used annually throughout Florida for
mosquito control.
   The last Medfly infestation in South Florida was in 1987 when
five males were found in Hialeah. The last major outbreak to affect
Florida's commercial groves spread across 28 counties in 1956.
