<LEADPARA>  Walking or driving around the West Valley you might not be able to see the
forest for the trees. But it's there -- a huge urban forest.;    And bad
things have entered that forest -- drought, disease and freezing temperatures.
As a result the trees, sometimes called the "lungs of a city" because of their
oxygen-producing capabilities, are wheezing.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Extra 3  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  URBAN FOREST WHEEZING
DROUGHT, BEETLES, FREEZE HIT TREES  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "The general health is weakened. No question about it," said Bob Bryant,
director of parks, forestry and maintenance for the town of Los Gatos. "It's
the worst I've experienced in 25 years.";    Already stressed by drought and
then punched with a chilly fist last December and January, a large number of
trees could be dead or dying. The extent of the damage won't be known until
the spring.;    "My recommendation is not to do a thing until April to see
what kind of budding and new growth we get and then we will know what trees to
prune and save and what trees will have to be removed," said Bryant.;    The
town has already applied for $130,000 from the state's Natural Disaster
Assistance Act to fund the replanting of trees. That amount would be necessary
if all the town-owned trees that are damaged die, according to Bryant,
representing what he terms a "worse case scenario.";    Officials in all the
West Valley communities say the problem with city-owned trees hasn't yet
become a huge one, but they add that more trees than usual are having to be
removed and that their normal growth patterns are being affected.;    No more
than six to 10 trees have to be removed in a normal year in Campbell. This
season the total is already more than 20.;    Tree removals represent an
extremely small proportion of the thousands of city-owned trees which line the
streets and are in city parks, and the thousands more on private property. But
the aesthetic and environmental qualities of trees make them a priority
concern of both city officials and homeowners. Brown lawns are one thing.
Losing trees that took maybe 50 years to mature is another.;    How much more
serious the problem might become depends on how many trees end up dead or
unsalvageable, coupled with budgetary constraints and whatever water
allocations are available later this year.;    "We'll have to move our water
resources around, but basically the way I'm viewing it is that ground- cover
turf can be easily replaced, but a tree is a 20-, 30- or 50-year investment,"
said Mike DeGroot, Campbell public works superintendent.;    Last summer, the
city stored non-potable (non-drinkable) water secured from the San Jose Water
Treatment Plant and used a city water truck to irrigate critical areas.;   
Most of the trees Campbell plants are Chinese pistachio, Raywood Ash, Bradford
Pear, and flowering plum. The city this season has already lost quite a few
young eucalyptus, some ficus, ash and evergreen pear trees, according to
DeGroot.;    Monterey pines, which dot its hillsides, have proven to be the
biggest problem in Saratoga. The drought-weakened trees are infested with bark
beetles.;    "Monterey pines have been planted extensively on hillsides,
primarily on private property, and a number of them have had to be removed,"
said Bob Rizzo, Saratoga parks superintendent. "There are also a lot of
eucalyptus and California pepper trees I've noticed looking real bad.";    It
was reported last summer that the bark beetle infestation had become
widespread in San Jose, affecting dozens of trees in older parks and
neighborhoods. Particularly hard hit were Rainbow Park in West San Jose and
Butcher Park in the Cambrian area.;    Rizzo said oaks and other
drought-resistant trees are doing fairly well and there isn't a large problem
with city-owned trees in Saratoga. That could change if the drought
continues.;    Riparian trees, those along lakes and creekbeds, have been
stressed as their root systems struggle in dry and compacted soil.;    The
white alders at Vasona Park in Los Gatos have been hard hit, as have
eucalyptus. "I suspect the Australian willow has been badly burned in the
freeze," said Bryant.;    Removing and replanting trees is a big expense for
municipalities. Likewise, homeowners could be faced with large bills dealing
with the trees on their property.;    "Those folks could be in a world of
hurt," said Bryant.  </TEXT>
